    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (73.62) leading the charge as our most critical asset. Facing the right-handed Leiter, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** benefits from a favorable pitching matchup and a slow delivery profile that significantly increases our expected stolen base yield\u2014a high-priority metric for this team. **Josh Naylor** (69.01) and **Seiya Suzuki** (65.18) provide strong core production; **Seiya Suzuki** is particularly well-positioned against the vulnerable Randy V\u00e1squez (5.43 xERA), while **Josh Naylor** capitalizes on a high-ceiling matchup that offsets his dynamic platoon disadvantage against the lefty Prielipp. **Giancarlo Stanton** (61.91) also earns a strong start, maintaining a consistent floor in the middle of the order against Leiter.\n\nWhile the bottom of the order carries some inherent risk, **Dalton Rushing** (60.67) and **Alex Freeland** (54.54) are buoyed by a favorable wind forecast and a soft matchup against Chris Paddack. **Jose Caballero** (50.13) occupies our most volatile spot; despite a negative platoon adjustment, his inclusion remains strategic due to the high likelihood of a stolen base opportunity against a slow-working pitcher. **Trevor Story** (53.79) sits near the margin, as his score is suppressed by the elite skill set of opposing pitcher Cease, but his historical ability to capitalize on base-stealing opportunities keeps him in the starting nine over the currently inactive **Corbin Carroll**, **James Wood**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, and **Vinnie Pasquantino**, all of whom are unavailable due to team off-days.\n\nThe primary risk today involves our heavy reliance on \"Lineup Pending\" designations for **Dalton Rushing**, **Luis Campusano**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Alex Freeland**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Seiya Suzuki**. Should any of these players move down in the batting order or catch a surprise day off, we may see a significant degradation in their efficiency scores. **Luis Campusano** (48.96) remains our most vulnerable starter; he barely clears the threshold for active status, and any late-breaking lineup shifts could force a pivot to avoid wasting a game cap on a marginal performance. We continue to monitor the status of **Mickey Moniak**, **Austin Riley**, **Brice Turang**, **Gabriel Moreno**, **Max Muncy**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Kyle Karros**, **Carson Williams**, and **Travis Bazzana** for any sudden bench depth requirements.",
